  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-22 19:44 UTC \u2014 [P4: Alpha Research] Add Audit Logging So Suppressed Copy Input Still Leaves Usable Diagnostics\n\n**Task:** Define how the bot should log and expose copy suppression once the defensive consumer patch is live, so shadow analysis still sees why copy influence was ignored.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- The current copy-adjustment block already writes `details[\"COPY\"]` strings like:\n  - `\u2705 bullish@100`\n  - `\u26a0\ufe0f bearish@100`\n  - `\u26a0\ufe0f low_conf bullish@30`\n  - `\u2014`\n- That means the cleanest defensive extension is to add suppression-specific audit strings rather than invent a new downstream logging channel.\n- Wrote new implementation artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v9j-copy-suppression-audit-logging.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is important because a freeze without diagnostics becomes invisible debt. The bot may behave correctly live but we would lose the ability to understand when copy was suppressed and why. Good defensive logic should be both safe and auditable.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Add suppression audit strings inside `details[\"COPY\"]`, for example:\n  - `\ud83e\uddca unstable`\n  - `\ud83d\udd52 stale`\n  - `\ud83d\udcc9 insufficient_sample`\n- Emit one concise log line with suppression reason and any available bias/confidence context.\n- Keep the existing conviction detail format intact.\n\n**Next:** On the next P4 heartbeat, draft the exact line-level changes to the copy-adjustment branch so these new suppression states appear cleanly alongside the existing `\u2705`, `\u26a0\ufe0f`, and `\u2014` states.\n\n---\n## 2026-04-22 19:28 UTC \u2014 [P3: Strategy Development] Specify the Exact `read_copy_signals()` Patch Without Changing Its Interface\n\n**Task:** Draft the exact consumer-side patch behavior for `trading_bot.py::read_copy_signals()`, using the new additive schema while preserving the current bot interface.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- The current function is already a clean seam:\n  - it loads the signal JSON\n  - checks timestamp age\n  - suppresses only `data_quality == \"stale\"`\n  - returns `(market_bias, confidence)` or `(None, 0)`\n- That means the defensive patch can be fully interface-preserving.\n- Wrote new implementation artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v9i-read-copy-signals-consumer-patch.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is the exact kind of patch you want in live code. No signature changes, no downstream churn, just stricter suppression criteria and better diagnostics. The rest of the bot does not need to know anything changed.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Keep `read_copy_signals()` return shape unchanged.\n- Add suppression for:\n  - `data_quality in {\"stale\", \"unstable\", \"insufficient_sample\"}`\n  - `copy_quality.copy_sample_unstable == true`\n- Log the suppression reason.\n- If the new fields are absent, preserve legacy behavior.\n\n**Next:** On the next P3 heartbeat, draft the exact log messages and detail-string behavior so suppressed copy input still leaves useful audit trace",
